helped round out our little lighting team

40
00:02:05,927 --> 00:02:07,087
into something fantastic.

41
00:02:07,808 --> 00:02:10,649
Now you may be thinking, what is lighting?

42
00:02:11,189 --> 00:02:12,870
That question comes up all the time.

43
00:02:14,311 --> 00:02:16,072
You know what it is, but what does it mean?

44
00:02:17,383 --> 00:02:18,885
Well, it's not just adding lights.

45
00:02:19,425 --> 00:02:22,147
It's adding fog, weather, color correction,

46
00:02:22,247 --> 00:02:24,328
and anything else that makes a picture feel finished

47
00:02:24,348 --> 00:02:25,209
at the end of production.

48
00:02:26,750 --> 00:02:28,471
In games, we have to wear a lot of hats,

49
00:02:28,991 --> 00:02:32,074
compositor, color artist, sometimes even matte painter.

50
00:02:32,934 --> 00:02:35,256
Because of all this, lighting plays a huge role

51
00:02:35,336 --> 00:02:36,276
in the final look of the game.

52
00:02:38,376 --> 00:02:39,877
As one of the final steps in production,

53
00:02:40,237 --> 00:02:42,979
it's our job to add that last bit of life into a piece.

54
00:02:43,539 --> 00:02:45,300
Whether that's in a level or cinematic,

55
00:02:45,420 --> 00:02:47,201
we work on enhancing what's already there.

56
00:02:48,642 --> 00:02:50,823
We make sure our characters are lit in flattering ways,

57
00:02:51,224 --> 00:02:52,885
we add depth to an already rich world,

58
00:02:53,265 --> 00:02:55,526
and we call attention to the best parts of a product.

59
00:02:58,068 --> 00:02:59,689
Now, a huge responsibility of our job

60
00:02:59,749 --> 00:03:01,470
is to determine the mood of a space.

61
00:03:02,090 --> 00:03:04,171
Not only do we need to make sure that the level is playable

62
00:03:04,491 --> 00:03:05,372
and visually appealing,

63
00:03:05,472 --> 00:03:07,353
but we need to make sure that it tells a story.

64
00:03:08,481 --> 00:03:10,062
So much of that comes down to atmosphere.

65
00:03:10,743 --> 00:03:13,064
Brightness, contrast, fog, color,

66
00:03:13,805 --> 00:03:16,067
all of these things make lighting nearly as vital

67
00:03:16,087 --> 00:03:17,628
to storytelling as the dialogue,

68
00:03:18,909 --> 00:03:22,231
which is why lighting can take an image from this to this.

69
00:03:25,114 --> 00:03:26,675
Here we can see an approximation

70
00:03:26,735 --> 00:03:30,558
of what ripped apart looks like before lighting and after.

71
00:03:32,039 --> 00:03:33,059
It might not seem like much,

72
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:35,201
but all these individual tools I've been mentioning

73
00:03:35,241 --> 00:03:38,083
come together to impact every pixel on the screen.

74
00:03:39,710 --> 00:03:42,672
When lighting is done well, it's not something most people will ever notice.

75
00:03:43,533 --> 00:03:46,635
I've always said that you can build the most amazing environments and fill it with the

76
00:03:46,695 --> 00:03:51,078
most incredible characters, but if lighting's not strong, everyone's work suffers.

77
00:03:52,619 --> 00:03:56,442
Like we said, it's our job to bring an image to the finish line, but let's start at the

78
00:03:56,462 --> 00:03:56,782
beginning.

79
00:03:59,384 --> 00:04:02,626
We knew going into this project that we were going to have a big task ahead of us.

80
00:04:03,606 --> 00:04:07,049
But as anyone who's been through pre-production knows, the only thing we can be certain of

81
00:04:07,089 --> 00:04:09,230
in the early days is that everything is going to change.

82
00:04:10,199 --> 00:04:13,662
So this pre-production phase was focused on the things we knew we could control,

83
00:04:14,123 --> 00:04:18,347
identifying our pillars, our areas of concern, and making a game plan.

84
00:04:19,188 --> 00:04:20,749
Let's dive into a bit of what that looked like.

85
00:04:21,950 --> 00:04:23,372
I am going to start with a bit of a cheat here.

86
00:04:24,092 --> 00:04:27,876
Our biggest hurdle didn't actually happen in pre-production, but it's hard to talk about

87
00:04:28,056 --> 00:04:30,879
anybody making a game in the past few years without addressing COVID.

88
00:04:31,960 --> 00:04:32,080
It's...

89
00:04:33,464 --> 00:04:37,586
We had a pretty small team, and it was forming right when COVID had started,

90
00:04:37,606 --> 00:04:40,287
and we were all just starting to work from home.

91
00:04:41,227 --> 00:04:42,988
And it was a stressful and uncertain time.

92
00:04:44,469 --> 00:04:46,149
No one really knew how all this was going to work,

93
00:04:46,329 --> 00:04:49,251
and frankly, work wasn't even really anyone's primary concern.

94
00:04:50,411 --> 00:04:53,993
That said, we have an incredible IT team at Insomniac Games

95
00:04:54,833 --> 00:04:58,414
that did amazing work getting us all going really quickly

96
00:04:58,494 --> 00:04:59,835
in our work-from-home transition.

97
00:05:00,535 --> 00:05:02,456
And it's hard to figure out how it could have gone any smoother.

98
00:05:03,723 --> 00:05:07,605
As for the day-to-day work, we knew that every day wasn't going to be the most productive.

99
00:05:07,665 --> 00:05:10,166
Some days were just going to be tough, and that was always going to be okay.

100
00:05:10,507 --> 00:05:12,968
We knew the priority is everyone had to take care of themselves,

101
00:05:13,928 --> 00:05:16,389
and we needed to keep our focus on that.

102
00:05:17,550 --> 00:05:25,213
But I also think I speak for the team when I say that this really colorful, silly, and super fun game was kind of what we needed.

103
00:05:25,433 --> 00:05:28,635
It was a nice distraction during a really strange time.

104
00:05:29,924 --> 00:05:31,806
Jumping back to our pre-production hurdles,

105
00:05:33,507 --> 00:05:35,108
one of the first big ones that we

106
00:05:35,168 --> 00:05:36,509
knew we were going to deal with was

107
00:05:36,549 --> 00:05:38,511
that this was a pretty sizable game,

108
00:05:39,131 --> 00:05:41,393
and we were going to do it with a pretty slim crew.

109
00:05:42,614 --> 00:05:44,595
Small teams can present workload issues,

110
00:05:44,675 --> 00:05:47,718
and you have to work through giving people

111
00:05:47,758 --> 00:05:49,699
the right combination of folks in place.

112
00:05:53,012 --> 00:05:54,753
to make sure that you're playing to everybody's strengths.

113
00:05:55,833 --> 00:05:57,194
It's a challenge I really enjoy,

114
00:05:57,534 --> 00:05:59,255
and I really like working with a small team.

115
00:05:59,695 --> 00:06:01,416
It gives everybody a little bit of an opportunity

116
00:06:01,436 --> 00:06:03,377
to handle different variety of tasks,

117
00:06:03,898 --> 00:06:04,838
but it is a challenge,

118
00:06:04,878 --> 00:06:06,539
and one that we knew we needed to take serious.

119
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:10,601
Also, the camaraderie and communication

120
00:06:10,621 --> 00:06:12,022
seems to be great when you have a small team.

121
00:06:14,505 --> 00:06:15,866
Hurdle number two was a pretty big one,

122
00:06:16,127 --> 00:06:17,769
and it was one that I think anybody working

123
00:06:17,789 --> 00:06:21,333
in a launch title window can understand.

124
00:06:21,393 --> 00:06:24,898
We weren't really sure how best to push forward on the PS5

125
00:06:24,938 --> 00:06:27,721
because PS5 was still being worked on when we'd started.

126
00:06:30,244 --> 00:06:32,327
So we needed to be wise about how we set

127
00:06:32,407 --> 00:06:33,709
our lofty visual goals.

128
00:06:35,551 --> 00:06:37,491
We knew we were going to have caps.

129
00:06:37,671 --> 00:06:39,092
We knew we were going to be able to push things,

130
00:06:39,152 --> 00:06:41,392
but we weren't sure exactly where our new baseline

131
00:06:41,432 --> 00:06:41,912
was going to be.

132
00:06:42,413 --> 00:06:43,673
We weren't sure what kinds of things

133
00:06:43,713 --> 00:06:45,093
we were going to be able to afford now.

134
00:06:46,073 --> 00:06:47,954
And we knew that we were going to have to establish

135
00:06:47,994 --> 00:06:48,734
where our limits were.

136
00:06:51,235 --> 00:06:53,375
But honestly, one of the biggest hurdles that we dealt with

137
00:06:53,435 --> 00:06:55,796
really early in production was understanding

138
00:06:55,816 --> 00:06:58,556
that we needed to make a clear generational leap in quality

139
00:06:58,616 --> 00:07:00,837
over the last Ratchet and Clank game on PS4.

140
00:07:01,217 --> 00:07:02,217
And that game was stunning.

141
00:07:03,117 --> 00:07:05,839
It was lauded at the time for its amazing visual fidelity,

142
00:07:05,879 --> 00:07:07,821
and there was a real concern that we needed to figure out

143
00:07:07,861 --> 00:07:10,362
exactly how we were going to improve on an already

144
00:07:10,503 --> 00:07:13,305
outstanding foundation in a way that shows the promise

145
00:07:13,345 --> 00:07:14,225
of next-gen lighting.

146
00:07:16,527 --> 00:07:18,188
So, where did we start?

147
00:07:18,808 --> 00:07:22,111
We needed to start identifying exactly which areas

148
00:07:22,151 --> 00:07:23,212
we knew we could improve on.

149
00:07:24,092 --> 00:07:26,094
First off, we wanted to make artistic advances

150
00:07:26,154 --> 00:07:27,755
to make the game feel more cinematic.

151
00:07:28,235 --> 00:07:29,896
We wanted the player to feel like they were living

152
00:07:29,936 --> 00:07:31,938
inside of a movie instead of just playing a game.

153
00:07:33,512 --> 00:07:35,573
Second, we wanted to showcase technical improvements

154
00:07:35,613 --> 00:07:37,574
in both reflections and indirect lighting

155
00:07:37,634 --> 00:07:39,335
to make the world feel more realistic.

156
00:07:40,236 --> 00:07:43,298
And last, we wanted to expand on our post-processing

157
00:07:43,398 --> 00:07:45,859
to match that of feature animation levels of polish,

158
00:07:46,419 --> 00:07:48,420
further refining and implementing bloom,

159
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:50,681
chromatic aberration, color correction,

160
00:07:50,842 --> 00:07:52,302
all that fun post stuff,

161
00:07:52,943 --> 00:07:54,564
just really to dial in the polish.

162
00:07:55,504 --> 00:07:57,565
And while we had some ambitious goals here,

163
00:07:57,945 --> 00:08:00,046
luckily we weren't starting completely from scratch.

164
00:08:01,397 --> 00:08:04,118
Insomniac was just coming off of the huge success

165
00:08:04,178 --> 00:08:07,218
of Marvel's Spider-Man, and with it came a lot of knowledge

166
00:08:07,958 --> 00:08:09,739
about best practices and workflows.

167
00:08:10,559 --> 00:08:12,659
As I mentioned before, we're still learning the limits

168
00:08:12,699 --> 00:08:14,099
of what a PS5 can do,

169
00:08:14,739 --> 00:08:16,920
but we know what a PS4 is capable of.

170
00:08:17,520 --> 00:08:18,580
So we started with that,

171
00:08:18,740 --> 00:08:20,440
knowing that we would be able to push things more

172
00:08:20,480 --> 00:08:21,281
as production went on.

173
00:08:23,641 --> 00:08:25,361
We started from a foundation of making sure

174
00:08:25,381 --> 00:08:26,962
that we followed a PBR pipeline

175
00:08:27,002 --> 00:08:28,302
that had a foundation in lighting

176
00:08:28,342 --> 00:08:29,942
that could be measured in the real world.

177
00:08:30,706 --> 00:08:35,433
we would make sure that our contrast ratio of direct and indirect light matched real-world measurements.

178
00:08:36,153 --> 00:08:42,783
And a major lesson that we learned on Marvel's Spider-Man was that the act of lighting a space tended to have stronger results when we kept things simple,

179
00:08:43,924 --> 00:08:45,066
which we'll explain more in a bit.

180
00:08:47,274 --> 00:08:48,756
So I've been talking about the pipeline.

181
00:08:48,976 --> 00:08:50,417
What specifically does that mean

182
00:08:50,497 --> 00:08:51,759
for the Insomniac lighting team?

183
00:08:52,159 --> 00:08:53,560
We'll get into the details in a moment,

184
00:08:53,661 --> 00:08:55,402
but essentially this is our roadmap

185
00:08:55,462 --> 00:08:58,385
for clean, simple, predictable lighting practices

186
00:08:58,445 --> 00:08:59,006
for our games.

187
00:08:59,727 --> 00:09:02,089
By using these steps, we're able to pace ourselves,

188
00:09:02,249 --> 00:09:04,552
keeping polish for the last steps in the process,

189
00:09:04,672 --> 00:09:06,033
and instead focus on getting

190
00:09:06,073 --> 00:09:07,415
the fundamentals right up front.

191
00:09:10,058 --> 00:09:13,720
The first place that we always start when we're lighting a level is exposure.

192
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:16,562
Exposure is really the foundation of everything that we do.

193
00:09:16,962 --> 00:09:21,124
It affects everything that we do afterwards, and we need to get it locked down early.

194
00:09:21,864 --> 00:09:24,185
Not setting this correctly at the beginning can be tricky,

195
00:09:24,245 --> 00:09:26,266
because the impact is not immediately obvious

196
00:09:26,366 --> 00:09:29,228
and can really start to become more obvious as production rolls on.

197
00:09:30,268 --> 00:09:34,590
An improper exposure can cause inconsistency in glowing materials and visual effects

198
00:09:34,670 --> 00:09:37,351
and in the intensity of placed light values throughout the game.

199
00:09:38,145 --> 00:09:43,307
It can also lead to situations where the player will walk into a really bright area and the camera doesn't adjust,

200
00:09:43,587 --> 00:09:45,668
or we walk into a dark area and it doesn't get brighter.

201
00:09:46,729 --> 00:09:51,051
Essentially, we need to treat this step less like an artistic or an aesthetic step,

202
00:09:51,471 --> 00:09:55,873
and more like a technical first step that is consistent with values that we've set across the game.

203
00:09:56,574 --> 00:09:59,655
What we're aiming for in our first pass of lighting is predictability.

204
00:10:02,064 --> 00:10:04,125
Let's take a look at an example of the impact

205
00:10:04,165 --> 00:10:06,205
of different exposure settings can make on a scene

206
00:10:06,225 --> 00:10:08,286
in a way that isn't entirely obvious to the lighter

207
00:10:08,306 --> 00:10:09,106
when they're starting out.

208
00:10:09,906 --> 00:10:11,307
We have a really simple hallway here.

209
00:10:11,747 --> 00:10:13,548
The results in the right and left,

210
00:10:13,608 --> 00:10:15,008
if you're only looking at the lighting,

211
00:10:15,128 --> 00:10:16,448
are not really very different,

212
00:10:16,989 --> 00:10:18,809
but there is a very noticeable difference

213
00:10:18,849 --> 00:10:20,730
in how bright this green cube is getting.

214
00:10:21,290 --> 00:10:23,951
The reason that exposure has such an impact on materials

215
00:10:24,031 --> 00:10:25,451
is because essentially we're brightening

216
00:10:25,491 --> 00:10:26,851
and darkening the entire scene,

217
00:10:26,951 --> 00:10:29,152
and it's bringing things like emissive materials

218
00:10:29,432 --> 00:10:31,293
along with it on the right.

219
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:38,802
Think of a good comparison or a good example to think of

220
00:10:38,883 --> 00:10:40,083
is like a cell phone screen.

221
00:10:40,323 --> 00:10:41,724
If you open your phone up,

222
00:10:41,804 --> 00:10:44,366
you have auto brightness turned off.

223
00:10:44,966 --> 00:10:47,688
If you open this up in a dark room, a movie theater,

224
00:10:47,808 --> 00:10:48,748
everybody's gonna look at you

225
00:10:48,788 --> 00:10:51,470
because you've got this really bright glowing screen

226
00:10:51,490 --> 00:10:52,191
in front of your face.

227
00:10:52,711 --> 00:10:54,212
If you take the same phone outside,

228
00:10:54,232 --> 00:10:55,252
it's gonna be really dim.

229
00:10:55,773 --> 00:10:58,054
We have to think about those sorts of things

230
00:10:58,094 --> 00:11:00,055
when we're trying to set our exposure.

231
00:11:03,256 --> 00:11:05,856
Many of the assets that are going to go into our lighting

232
00:11:06,197 --> 00:11:07,697
may not come in for weeks or months,

233
00:11:07,757 --> 00:11:09,197
so we are not going to immediately see

234
00:11:09,237 --> 00:11:11,178
these sorts of things until later down the road,

235
00:11:11,218 --> 00:11:12,798
which is why we need to be predictable

236
00:11:13,398 --> 00:11:14,598
in the lighting that we set up.

237
00:11:15,098 --> 00:11:17,379
We not only want our lighting to be predictable for us,

238
00:11:17,539 --> 00:11:20,820
we want it to be predictable for everybody across the game.

239
00:11:23,760 --> 00:11:25,321
Once we have established our exposure,

240
00:11:25,621 --> 00:11:27,321
we are going to set our key light intensity.

241
00:11:27,881 --> 00:11:30,002
Again, this is not a value that is set for aesthetics,

242
00:11:30,142 --> 00:11:32,702
but a value that is coordinated with the value of the exposure.

243
00:11:33,557 --> 00:11:34,738
Throughout the work on the level,

244
00:11:35,118 --> 00:11:37,880
we like to treat these two settings as locked variables

245
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:40,402
that the rest of the lighting work is balanced around,

246
00:11:40,842 --> 00:11:43,925
whether it be light intensity, fog brightness, god rays,

247
00:11:44,425 --> 00:11:44,825
you name it.

248
00:11:45,225 --> 00:11:47,127
Everything's impacted by these first two things.

249
00:11:47,867 --> 00:11:50,509
This ensures that we're working on the same baseline

250
00:11:51,090 --> 00:11:53,151
for the whole lighting team across the game

251
00:11:53,331 --> 00:11:54,692
and making sure we have consistency.

252
00:11:57,557 --> 00:12:00,079
The next big step for us is to get a good ratio

253
00:12:00,119 --> 00:12:02,000
between direct and indirect lighting.

254
00:12:02,541 --> 00:12:04,563
Almost all of Ripped Apart is taking place

255
00:12:04,623 --> 00:12:06,865
in large outdoor areas, and in every level,

256
00:12:06,905 --> 00:12:09,347
we're starting with a wide, majestic vista shot.

257
00:12:10,107 --> 00:12:11,689
And of course, these are all alien worlds,

258
00:12:11,729 --> 00:12:14,792
so matching earth lighting ratios may not seem necessary,

259
00:12:14,872 --> 00:12:17,454
but I felt like after doing a lot of testing early on

260
00:12:17,474 --> 00:12:19,175
where we were just kind of eyeballing things

261
00:12:19,716 --> 00:12:21,417
and sort of trying to get in the ballpark,

262
00:12:21,497 --> 00:12:22,698
things weren't really clicking.

263
00:12:23,506 --> 00:12:27,649
starting from a strong place where lighting matched what our eyes are familiar with

264
00:12:27,889 --> 00:12:29,530
and gave us better results quicker.

265
00:12:30,711 --> 00:12:33,413
To get it right, we want to know what the real-world ratio is.

266
00:12:33,713 --> 00:12:36,035
And this is a rather simple process if you have the equipment.

267
00:12:36,795 --> 00:12:39,957
You'll need a digital SLR camera and a gray calibration card.

268
00:12:40,538 --> 00:12:42,879
You set the camera to a fully manual mode

269
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:47,242
so that it'll override anything the camera's trying to do for you,

270
00:12:47,482 --> 00:12:50,825
including shutter speed, f-stop, ISO, all that good stuff.

271
00:12:51,978 --> 00:12:55,000
You can refer to a photography guide for best settings to use

272
00:12:55,100 --> 00:12:56,721
for the time of day that you're shooting in.

273
00:12:57,381 --> 00:13:00,723
But essentially, once you've set your F-stop

274
00:13:00,783 --> 00:13:02,884
and shutter speed, you don't change it again.

275
00:13:05,406 --> 00:13:06,927
So you're gonna go outside with your camera

276
00:13:07,447 --> 00:13:10,288
and you're gonna snap a picture of your gray card

277
00:13:10,389 --> 00:13:11,289
in direct sunlight.

278
00:13:11,709 --> 00:13:13,250
And then you're gonna turn away from the sun

279
00:13:13,290 --> 00:13:14,271
and snap another picture.

280
00:13:15,151 --> 00:13:16,892
You can also just go into a shadow area

281
00:13:16,952 --> 00:13:18,033
like I did in the image here.

282
00:13:18,810 --> 00:13:19,290
And there you go.

283
00:13:19,870 --> 00:13:22,092
Take these pictures into a photo editing software,

284
00:13:22,192 --> 00:13:24,174
desaturate it, and get an RGB reading,

285
00:13:24,214 --> 00:13:26,796
and figure out how many times brighter the sunlit card is

286
00:13:26,876 --> 00:13:28,136
than the card in indirect light.

287
00:13:29,237 --> 00:13:29,818
And there you have it.

288
00:13:29,978 --> 00:13:32,960
You have a direct to indirect lighting contrast ratio.

289
00:13:33,560 --> 00:13:35,302
For a sunny Los Angeles afternoon,

290
00:13:35,342 --> 00:13:37,703
we ended up with roughly a three to one ratio here.

291
00:13:39,905 --> 00:13:41,626
The next step is to just recreate

292
00:13:41,686 --> 00:13:43,227
this exact process in InGen.

293
00:13:43,908 --> 00:13:46,130
We're looking for the same three to one ratio

294
00:13:46,210 --> 00:13:47,651
in our direct versus indirect.

295
00:13:48,289 --> 00:13:51,892
If key light and adaptation are locked, this process should run rather smoothly.

296
00:13:52,433 --> 00:13:56,396
If it's not, it might be a good idea to either brighten or darken your sky and rebake until

297
00:13:56,416 --> 00:13:57,917
you reach the expected ratio.

298
00:13:59,919 --> 00:14:03,862
The next steps of the pipeline is actually placing our lights, prefabs, and probes.

299
00:14:04,837 --> 00:14:08,159
The big goal for this project was to try to work simple and realistic.

300
00:14:08,779 --> 00:14:12,661
Every light needed to have a motivated light source, and we didn't want to have any phantom

301
00:14:12,701 --> 00:14:17,704
lights on ratchet, or manipulate the bounce or strength of our bounce light anyway.

302
00:14:18,264 --> 00:14:19,925
We wanted to be simple and PBR.

303
00:14:20,985 --> 00:14:25,288
In this example of Rivet's Hideout, a majority of this room is lit by just a few very large

304
00:14:25,348 --> 00:14:25,628
lights.

305
00:14:28,014 --> 00:14:30,996
While generally seen as a negative to have overlap of this extent,

306
00:14:31,536 --> 00:14:34,558
we found that this actually caused less performance issues to deal with,

307
00:14:35,139 --> 00:14:36,760
and it kept our setup simple.

308
00:14:37,120 --> 00:14:40,922
After all, it's easier to dial 3 to 5 lights than 10 to 15.

309
00:14:41,923 --> 00:14:44,164
And aesthetically, we got more realistic bounce light

310
00:14:44,265 --> 00:14:46,366
and more natural adaptation in our exposure.

311
00:14:48,990 --> 00:14:50,590
From then on, it's an adjustments game,

312
00:14:51,011 --> 00:14:52,791
tweaking and rebaking until you get something

313
00:14:52,811 --> 00:14:53,552
that you're happy with.

314
00:14:54,312 --> 00:14:56,133
It's important that you rebake continuously.

315
00:14:56,693 --> 00:14:58,014
The game is in constant flux

316
00:14:58,054 --> 00:15:00,455
and other departments are always adding things to levels

317
00:15:00,515 --> 00:15:01,855
and you don't want any surprises

318
00:15:01,895 --> 00:15:02,776
midway through production.

319
00:15:05,257 --> 00:15:06,777
So after you get it technically correct

320
00:15:06,877 --> 00:15:08,238
and in the ballpark artistically,

321
00:15:08,538 --> 00:15:10,599
it's time for the exciting part, post-process.

322
00:15:11,676 --> 00:15:13,257
You don't want to do this step too early,

323
00:15:13,337 --> 00:15:15,879
because anything you're doing to add visual flourish now

324
00:15:16,360 --> 00:15:18,241
can actually complicate your initial setup

325
00:15:18,301 --> 00:15:20,203
and lead to technical mistakes later on.

326
00:15:23,345 --> 00:15:26,227
But all that being said, the post-process step in production

327
00:15:26,287 --> 00:15:28,309
is where a project can really find its voice.

328
00:15:29,358 --> 00:15:32,240
In Rift Apart, we were going for a more futuristic, colorful look.

329
00:15:32,821 --> 00:15:36,784
We wanted lens flares that would make Star Trek jealous, and a color scheme that would

330
00:15:36,804 --> 00:15:39,066
make players excited to see more.

331
00:15:39,746 --> 00:15:43,649
That meant adjusting the color correction to saturate the scene and push the contrast

332
00:15:43,670 --> 00:15:45,171
for a more cinematic feel.

333
00:15:45,891 --> 00:15:49,975
It also meant adjusting the fog to soften the overall look of the piece to match the

334
00:15:50,015 --> 00:15:51,336
quality of feature animation.

335
00:15:52,645 --> 00:15:55,107
We mentioned earlier that lighters are the finishers of an image,

336
00:15:55,127 --> 00:15:56,508
and this is exactly what we mean.

337
00:15:57,128 --> 00:16:01,470
These final steps in the process can dramatically change the tone, style,

338
00:16:01,670 --> 00:16:03,051
and feel of a game completely.

339
00:16:03,671 --> 00:16:06,533
And that's why it's so important that everything is done correctly.

340
00:16:07,534 --> 00:16:10,856
Trying to polish lighting on work that wasn't built on a solid foundation

341
00:16:11,296 --> 00:16:13,097
is an immensely more difficult task,

342
00:16:13,597 --> 00:16:15,258
one that takes substantially more time

343
00:16:15,358 --> 00:16:18,300
and is likely to never hit the quality bar that we're looking for.

344
00:16:18,980 --> 00:16:20,481
We have an example of exactly that.

345
00:16:22,832 --> 00:16:24,752
This is a train station in Nefarious City

346
00:16:24,792 --> 00:16:27,654
that we've relit using a series of common workarounds

347
00:16:27,734 --> 00:16:28,994
and inefficient workflows.

348
00:16:30,615 --> 00:16:33,356
To start out, there's entirely too many lights in here.

349
00:16:33,416 --> 00:16:34,797
It's starting to flatten everything.

350
00:16:35,157 --> 00:16:36,617
And because we have so many lights,

351
00:16:37,198 --> 00:16:39,719
I had to start making several of them skip shadow casting

352
00:16:39,759 --> 00:16:41,620
because we were running into performance issues.

353
00:16:42,760 --> 00:16:44,281
Even that didn't help with performance,

354
00:16:44,301 --> 00:16:46,162
so I had to start having some of the lights

355
00:16:46,302 --> 00:16:47,642
only contribute to bounce light.

356
00:16:48,272 --> 00:16:50,133
And then we still had performance problems,

357
00:16:50,153 --> 00:16:51,975
so I reduced the fall-off of the lights.

358
00:16:52,135 --> 00:16:54,377
But because those lights were falling off so quickly,

359
00:16:54,397 --> 00:16:55,978
now I'm getting less bounce light.

360
00:16:56,378 --> 00:16:57,779
So then I'm adding more lights

361
00:16:58,059 --> 00:16:59,601
to get more fill into the corners.

362
00:17:01,082 --> 00:17:02,963
If this is starting to become our sound

363
00:17:02,983 --> 00:17:06,026
a little complicated and messy, it's because it is.

364
00:17:07,667 --> 00:17:09,689
This is a weird foundation to start with.

365
00:17:09,769 --> 00:17:12,011
And what we're doing is we're chasing our tails,

366
00:17:12,071 --> 00:17:14,012
trying to get a look that wasn't built

367
00:17:14,412 --> 00:17:15,473
on a strong foundation.

368
00:17:17,763 --> 00:17:20,265
So at first glance, you may not be able to see anything

369
00:17:20,786 --> 00:17:22,107
truly wrong with this scene.

370
00:17:22,227 --> 00:17:24,769
You can see the color tone and the mood we're going for,

371
00:17:24,869 --> 00:17:26,491
and most people wouldn't notice right away

372
00:17:26,631 --> 00:17:27,331
some of the issues.

373
00:17:27,912 --> 00:17:29,994
But compared against a scene lit using the pipeline

374
00:17:30,014 --> 00:17:30,834
that we've talked about,

375
00:17:30,854 --> 00:17:33,276
the difference can be pretty stark.

376
00:17:34,750 --> 00:17:36,790
When we light something correctly, it's just obvious.

377
00:17:37,050 --> 00:17:38,610
This is the same train station lit

378
00:17:38,710 --> 00:17:40,351
using the pipeline we've been outlining.

379
00:17:40,591 --> 00:17:43,211
This has fewer lights, somewhere around five lights,

380
00:17:43,271 --> 00:17:45,632
I think, are taking up most of the room.

381
00:17:46,232 --> 00:17:49,292
Better performance and easier to adjust for performance.

382
00:17:49,693 --> 00:17:53,073
If we needed to, oh, better performance,

383
00:17:53,113 --> 00:17:54,433
but if we need to dial those lights,

384
00:17:54,553 --> 00:17:57,834
we can narrow cones on four or five lights a lot quicker.

385
00:17:59,194 --> 00:18:00,515
We have got better player pathing

386
00:18:00,555 --> 00:18:01,815
and the material's already better.

387
00:18:02,095 --> 00:18:04,015
And bonus, it also just looks prettier.

388
00:18:04,726 --> 00:18:05,748
Let's take a look at the details.

389
00:18:07,510 --> 00:18:10,335
The image on the left is missing shadows from this platform.

390
00:18:10,835 --> 00:18:12,979
In some ways, it's hard to tell that there's even

391
00:18:12,999 --> 00:18:15,242
a platform present because the contrast is missing,

392
00:18:15,262 --> 00:18:16,764
and it's making the image harder to parse.

393
00:18:17,422 --> 00:18:22,564
One of the primary reasons we're losing contrast here is that the light above the platform isn't casting any shadows.

394
00:18:22,925 --> 00:18:28,447
It's a common technique to move to in the ages-long battle with making sure a game is performant,

395
00:18:28,547 --> 00:18:32,208
and in previous generations of hardware, it made a certain amount of sense to do this.

396
00:18:32,789 --> 00:18:36,850
In the past, we've all had to cut corners to keep the cost of lighting from impacting playability,

397
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:39,711
sacrificing visual fidelity for performance.

398
00:18:40,734 --> 00:18:44,856
But with the power of the PS5, we were determined to find other ways to get that performance back

399
00:18:44,936 --> 00:18:48,598
and not resort to tactics such as removing shadows from lights.

400
00:18:49,579 --> 00:18:54,001
We lit scenes with the idea that anything that a light is touching is casting a shadow,

401
00:18:54,501 --> 00:18:57,503
and anything else, and anything less, and we're losing immersion.

402
00:18:59,972 --> 00:19:02,912
The other issue we're running into here is player pathing.

403
00:19:03,432 --> 00:19:05,753
The blue of this light is supposed to act as a beacon

404
00:19:05,813 --> 00:19:07,393
and pop so that the player knows

405
00:19:07,473 --> 00:19:08,654
where they're supposed to exit.

406
00:19:09,114 --> 00:19:11,774
The image on the left does have this to some extent,

407
00:19:11,814 --> 00:19:13,835
but the colors aren't contrasting enough

408
00:19:14,115 --> 00:19:16,195
and the path to get there is less clear.

409
00:19:16,795 --> 00:19:18,456
In the image on the right, we have a clearer sense

410
00:19:18,496 --> 00:19:19,656
of not just where we need to go,

411
00:19:19,816 --> 00:19:21,917
but we can see the platforms leading me to it.

412
00:19:24,577 --> 00:19:27,038
And what about when we focus on our Lombax friend here?

413
00:19:27,720 --> 00:19:33,825
By over-optimizing a setup, we have a character that is not doing the PS5 or the Amazing Character team justice.

414
00:19:34,185 --> 00:19:37,528
Ratchet has lost his highlights, he looks extremely evenly lit.

415
00:19:38,348 --> 00:19:43,172
When the cinematics begin to roll in, we really want to make sure that the level lighting was done correctly,

416
00:19:43,252 --> 00:19:46,234
or the cinematics will become substantially more difficult to handle.

417
00:19:46,795 --> 00:19:49,837
The glowing mouth on Ratchet, on the left, is of major importance.

418
00:19:49,897 --> 00:19:54,640
As soon as he starts opening his mouth in a cinematic, it's going to look like his mouth is glowing.

419
00:19:55,190 --> 00:19:57,991
And there's not a lot that we can do in lighting to sort of bring that back.

420
00:20:00,592 --> 00:20:03,634
We're all trying to figure out how to balance aesthetics and performance,

421
00:20:03,734 --> 00:20:07,516
and all too often we find ourselves making tough decisions with the amount of lights,

422
00:20:07,976 --> 00:20:09,677
the fall off of lights, et cetera,

423
00:20:10,077 --> 00:20:14,239
making sure that a pretty picture isn't creating a game that, frankly, no one can play.

424
00:20:15,340 --> 00:20:19,802
But what we found is following the pipeline that we generally put ourselves in a good position

425
00:20:19,822 --> 00:20:23,444
to get a strong foundation of lighting that didn't have to make too many sacrifices.

426
00:20:24,083 --> 00:20:26,705
Our simpler setups were easier to tune for performance.

427
00:20:27,125 --> 00:20:28,646
We didn't need extraneous fill lights

428
00:20:28,706 --> 00:20:30,207
because our bounce light was done correctly

429
00:20:30,247 --> 00:20:31,008
in the first place.

430
00:20:31,708 --> 00:20:33,109
And if you look at the images above,

431
00:20:33,149 --> 00:20:34,690
the image on the left isn't awful,

432
00:20:34,930 --> 00:20:36,832
but it didn't quite hit the mark for a game

433
00:20:36,852 --> 00:20:39,374
that we wanted to show the promise of next gen lighting with.

434
00:20:39,934 --> 00:20:42,416
It's missing specular highlights and shadows

435
00:20:42,556 --> 00:20:45,818
and our characters and environment are suffering as a result.

436
00:20:48,060 --> 00:20:48,960
But with all that said,

437
00:20:49,180 --> 00:20:50,581
we're still making a video game here

438
00:20:50,681 --> 00:20:53,003
and it's impossible not to run into performance problems.

439
00:20:53,820 --> 00:20:55,841
To keep the game running smoothly,

440
00:20:56,322 --> 00:20:59,204
each department is allotted a certain percentage of power

441
00:20:59,685 --> 00:21:00,946
that we can use to affect the scene.

442
00:21:01,586 --> 00:21:03,588
In lighting's case, that's about eight milliseconds.

443
00:21:04,369 --> 00:21:06,070
Now that's not a hard and fast rule

444
00:21:06,170 --> 00:21:08,572
as different scenarios require different departments

445
00:21:08,592 --> 00:21:09,893
to take up more of that budget,

446
00:21:10,394 --> 00:21:11,795
but it's a strong place to start.

447
00:21:13,036 --> 00:21:15,698
Taking a look at a differently incorrectly lit scene,

448
00:21:16,119 --> 00:21:18,741
we can see that lighting is actually at 25 milliseconds here.

449
00:21:19,141 --> 00:21:21,083
That's three times the size of our budget.

450
00:21:22,048 --> 00:21:26,572
The reason lighting is so high here is because the scene was flooded with smaller, unoptimized lights

451
00:21:26,972 --> 00:21:31,435
that were inefficiently placed and covering mistakes that could have been easily fixed with proper care.

452
00:21:33,977 --> 00:21:39,220
That's why it's extremely important for us to tackle performance early and often because it affects the entire game.

453
00:21:41,867 --> 00:21:44,408
But of course, even when we do our job correctly,

454
00:21:44,588 --> 00:21:47,528
not everything is as simple as lighting a static room.

455
00:21:48,329 --> 00:21:49,629
If everything would have just sat still,

456
00:21:49,749 --> 00:21:51,549
our game would have been a heck of a lot easier to light.

457
00:21:52,249 --> 00:21:52,750
But it's not.

458
00:21:53,550 --> 00:21:54,850
And a big reason for that is because

459
00:21:54,870 --> 00:21:56,630
we were making a complicated game.

460
00:21:57,331 --> 00:21:58,631
One of the main features of the game

461
00:21:58,671 --> 00:22:00,171
is the ability to open a portal

462
00:22:00,591 --> 00:22:02,032
and enter a completely different level.

463
00:22:02,652 --> 00:22:05,532
That requires both levels to be open at the same time.

464
00:22:05,972 --> 00:22:07,233
And if we aren't lighting efficiently,

465
00:22:07,293 --> 00:22:10,193
that's two inefficiently lit levels at the same time.

466
00:22:11,273 --> 00:22:13,374
We built a game featured around fast loading,

467
00:22:13,735 --> 00:22:16,136
and lighting is one of the most expensive things in the game.

468
00:22:16,817 --> 00:22:18,298
That's why it's ultimately so important

469
00:22:18,338 --> 00:22:20,880
that we are responsible for our own work,

470
00:22:21,260 --> 00:22:23,201
and then look for creative solutions afterward.

471
00:22:24,883 --> 00:22:25,663
If you'd like to learn more

472
00:22:25,683 --> 00:22:27,444
about the incredible port of work in the game,

473
00:22:27,885 --> 00:22:30,006
you can check out Peter Kao's GDC talk,

474
00:22:30,346 --> 00:22:31,867
Shifts and Rifts Dimensional Tech

475
00:22:32,668 --> 00:22:33,989
on Ratchet and Clank Rift Apart.

476
00:22:37,018 --> 00:22:39,279
Here's a specific problem that we run into

477
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:40,961
with performance a lot,

478
00:22:41,621 --> 00:22:43,082
and it doesn't have an immediate answer.

479
00:22:43,563 --> 00:22:44,884
We did all the things we just said.

480
00:22:44,944 --> 00:22:47,385
We kept our lighting simple, we followed the pipeline.

481
00:22:47,926 --> 00:22:50,448
There's only one real driver of light in this scene,

482
00:22:50,508 --> 00:22:52,509
and it's the sun, and we need the sun.

483
00:22:53,890 --> 00:22:56,292
So if we've not gone crazy and placed a lot of lights,

484
00:22:56,672 --> 00:22:58,594
why is lighting double our budget?

485
00:22:59,114 --> 00:22:59,694
What happened here?

486
00:23:00,615 --> 00:23:01,436
Well, there's a few reasons.

487
00:23:01,696 --> 00:23:03,537
First off, the power of the PS5

488
00:23:03,597 --> 00:23:05,338
isn't just going to the lighting department.

489
00:23:06,025 --> 00:23:09,227
Everything that lights are hitting in this game is getting more expensive to light.

490
00:23:10,008 --> 00:23:15,733
Ripped Apart is known for its stunning environments, huge crowds, amazing characters, and active, vibrant scenes.

491
00:23:16,233 --> 00:23:18,916
And we love them, but they come at a cost.

492
00:23:19,776 --> 00:23:24,520
In this particular scene, what we are seeing is the cost of lighting a complex and dense environment

493
00:23:24,620 --> 00:23:27,923
without a lot in the way of optimization available for us on the lighting team.

494
00:23:28,804 --> 00:23:33,208
But we did accomplish our goal here of getting this very lovely shot performant, and let's dig into how.

495
00:23:35,490 --> 00:23:38,813
First off, our core team made incredible looking fur,

496
00:23:39,173 --> 00:23:41,295
but fur that somehow didn't tank our frame rate.

497
00:23:41,755 --> 00:23:44,778
For lighting, we skip rendering shadows for the fur shells

498
00:23:44,838 --> 00:23:46,900
and only render the base geo for shadow maps,

499
00:23:47,460 --> 00:23:49,442
which makes the shadow map rendering much cheaper

500
00:23:49,562 --> 00:23:51,364
and unintentionally, but neatly,

501
00:23:51,584 --> 00:23:54,066
also adds a sort of subsurface scattering effect

502
00:23:54,086 --> 00:23:54,527
to the fur.

503
00:23:55,448 --> 00:23:56,669
In the deferred lighting pass,

504
00:23:56,809 --> 00:23:59,932
we combine shadow maps with screen space contact shadows

505
00:23:59,972 --> 00:24:02,234
to pick fine shadows from the individual strands.

506
00:24:03,050 --> 00:24:05,130
This is all to say that often when we're lighting,

507
00:24:05,670 --> 00:24:07,511
the most expensive thing that we're dealing with

508
00:24:07,571 --> 00:24:09,631
are the characters, and it wasn't a problem

509
00:24:09,651 --> 00:24:11,852
that we ran into very often on Ratchet and Clank.

510
00:24:12,272 --> 00:24:14,753
And it's a really lovely game.

511
00:24:14,813 --> 00:24:16,593
It's great seeing the characters look this good

512
00:24:16,633 --> 00:24:17,593
and not cost a ton.

513
00:24:19,714 --> 00:24:21,654
For our second item, it's worth highlighting

514
00:24:21,714 --> 00:24:24,675
the gargantuan effort of our core team

515
00:24:24,755 --> 00:24:27,176
in exploring and implementing more and more refinements,

516
00:24:27,456 --> 00:24:29,576
optimizations, and improvements

517
00:24:29,596 --> 00:24:31,197
to our ray tracing throughout production.

518
00:24:31,895 --> 00:24:34,377
Ray tracing was always going to be a major feature of this game.

519
00:24:34,857 --> 00:24:37,339
Clank is, after all, a walking chrome ball,

520
00:24:37,579 --> 00:24:39,680
and you're seeing everything on him at all times.

521
00:24:40,801 --> 00:24:44,463
But that it was done this impressively with this minimal of an impact

522
00:24:44,523 --> 00:24:46,925
on performance is the reason that this team was able to win

523
00:24:46,985 --> 00:24:49,466
best technology award at this year's Dice Awards,

524
00:24:49,486 --> 00:24:52,508
and also a tech award last night at the GDC Awards.

525
00:24:53,509 --> 00:24:55,290
A major tip of the cap to this team.

526
00:24:57,353 --> 00:24:59,634
And then finally, we can't stress enough the importance

527
00:24:59,674 --> 00:25:01,035
of the hard work that the environment

528
00:25:01,075 --> 00:25:02,895
and character teams did, not only creating some

529
00:25:02,935 --> 00:25:05,096
of the most stunning environments

530
00:25:05,136 --> 00:25:08,177
and characters imaginable, but by putting in the work

531
00:25:08,217 --> 00:25:10,678
to optimize and ensure that LODs were in place.

532
00:25:12,758 --> 00:25:13,939
Circling back to this scene,

533
00:25:14,039 --> 00:25:15,959
lighting dropped almost nine milliseconds

534
00:25:16,039 --> 00:25:17,240
in a matter of a couple of weeks.

535
00:25:18,455 --> 00:25:20,416
due in large part to the work of people

536
00:25:20,456 --> 00:25:22,017
that I mentioned in the previous slides.

537
00:25:22,718 --> 00:25:24,559
I didn't really do anything here.

538
00:25:24,959 --> 00:25:26,380
Lighting dropped nine milliseconds

539
00:25:26,460 --> 00:25:29,222
with minimal input on lighting

540
00:25:29,302 --> 00:25:31,583
because lighting is affected by everybody else.

541
00:25:32,824 --> 00:25:35,626
We could have reduced shadow quality of our key light

542
00:25:35,746 --> 00:25:39,268
to make this work, but performance was really a team effort.

543
00:25:39,428 --> 00:25:41,749
Not all solutions are gonna be immediately apparent

544
00:25:42,210 --> 00:25:46,012
and we don't wanna try to bring out the big guns too early.

545
00:25:46,945 --> 00:25:52,188
So by working together, we're able to keep that incredible PS5 quality graphics look

546
00:25:52,408 --> 00:25:53,929
and run in frame at the same time.

547
00:25:56,050 --> 00:25:59,592
Okay, so now let's dive into the fun stuff, making the art.

548
00:26:00,433 --> 00:26:04,515
Following these rules and more allowed us to start with a good foundation for our lighting.

549
00:26:05,035 --> 00:26:08,938
But our next step was taking on what we'd learned and putting it into production

550
00:26:09,118 --> 00:26:10,319
and bringing it into our levels.

551
00:26:11,059 --> 00:26:12,560
Let's take a look at some of what we had to do.

552
00:26:14,201 --> 00:26:14,701
It was a lot.

553
00:26:16,669 --> 00:26:19,330
This was a massive linear game with expansive worlds.

554
00:26:19,750 --> 00:26:24,813
And on top of that, we had over one hour of cinematics taking place on 13 distinct planets

555
00:26:25,213 --> 00:26:26,954
that all needed to have their own unique look,

556
00:26:27,554 --> 00:26:31,876
some of them requiring multiple lighting setups for return visits or alternate dimensions.

557
00:26:32,576 --> 00:26:34,917
They each had to express a different mood and story

558
00:26:34,957 --> 00:26:38,799
while still feeling like it lived in the same universe with the same level of polish.

559
00:26:40,983 --> 00:26:44,025
Developing a look can be a daunting process that takes a village.

560
00:26:44,526 --> 00:26:47,268
From initial ideation all the way to the finished project,

561
00:26:47,668 --> 00:26:50,511
you're constantly working to hammer out the identity of a space.

562
00:26:51,311 --> 00:26:52,652
To explain how this process works,

563
00:26:53,113 --> 00:26:56,215
let's take a look at one of the levels that exemplifies not only the process,

564
00:26:56,656 --> 00:26:58,497
but the pivots we had to take during production.

565
00:26:59,338 --> 00:27:00,159
This is Blizzard,

566
00:27:00,959 --> 00:27:04,062
the level that underwent some of the most narrative and design changes

567
00:27:04,082 --> 00:27:05,183
throughout the game's lifetime.

568
00:27:07,328 --> 00:27:08,368
At the beginning of production,

569
00:27:08,749 --> 00:27:11,090
Lizard's narrative concept revolved heavily around

570
00:27:11,130 --> 00:27:13,912
those green crystals placed around the environment.

571
00:27:14,552 --> 00:27:16,693
Because of that, they wanted them heavily contrasted

572
00:27:16,733 --> 00:27:18,294
against a red monochromatic look.

573
00:27:19,335 --> 00:27:20,915
It also took place underground,

574
00:27:21,336 --> 00:27:22,616
meaning that the majority of the light

575
00:27:22,656 --> 00:27:25,078
had to come from the glow of the orange lava underneath.

576
00:27:26,699 --> 00:27:28,960
Most of our concept art was based heavily around

577
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:30,521
mood and theme of a space,

578
00:27:30,981 --> 00:27:32,682
and it's up to us to interpret that mood

579
00:27:32,742 --> 00:27:35,103
and make it something usable for practical level lighting.

580
00:27:37,065 --> 00:27:39,967
Early concept art, while helpful in finding a visual tone,

581
00:27:40,387 --> 00:27:42,548
doesn't always take into account player pathing.

582
00:27:43,009 --> 00:27:44,590
That's the need to guide a player

583
00:27:44,610 --> 00:27:46,391
throughout a level easily and naturally.

584
00:27:46,931 --> 00:27:48,473
And that's where things can get really tricky.

585
00:27:51,194 --> 00:27:53,376
After we tried to match the concept art in the game,

586
00:27:53,476 --> 00:27:56,058
we found we were contending with multiple issues here.

587
00:27:56,798 --> 00:27:58,199
We wanted the players to be impressed

588
00:27:58,259 --> 00:28:00,301
with the beautiful open vistas of the level,

589
00:28:00,401 --> 00:28:02,922
but we also needed them to know where to go.

590
00:28:04,045 --> 00:28:08,688
Because of the monochromatic color scheme, it was hard for the player to understand where the points of interest were.

591
00:28:09,429 --> 00:28:15,073
And without another source of light, it was difficult to point the player toward that next objective while still looking natural.

592
00:28:16,935 --> 00:28:21,979
Through exploration, we quickly determined that we needed to add another color to break up the monotony of the lava.

593
00:28:22,919 --> 00:28:26,862
We needed another source of light, but in an underground space, that can be really hard to come by.

594
00:28:28,081 --> 00:28:30,082
So after talking to narrative and environment,

595
00:28:30,142 --> 00:28:32,824
we determined that changing the location of the space

596
00:28:33,244 --> 00:28:34,985
was necessary to get the look we wanted.

597
00:28:37,587 --> 00:28:39,388
So we talked to our AD and concept team

598
00:28:39,448 --> 00:28:41,129
about possible artistic avenues.

599
00:28:41,729 --> 00:28:42,970
We went back and forth,

600
00:28:43,130 --> 00:28:45,231
trying and experimenting with color and theme.

601
00:28:45,672 --> 00:28:48,393
And eventually it was decided to knock out that back wall

602
00:28:48,713 --> 00:28:50,795
and get the key light and the sky contribution

603
00:28:50,855 --> 00:28:53,616
into the space to contrast nicely against all that orange.

604
00:28:55,061 --> 00:28:58,743
After they decided on this general concept look, it was our turn to bring it into the game.

605
00:29:01,505 --> 00:29:05,107
Like we said before, interpreting concept art can be really tricky.

606
00:29:05,947 --> 00:29:08,669
Even though we had solved some of those issues with color scheme,

607
00:29:09,129 --> 00:29:11,510
we were still having those same player pathing issues.

608
00:29:12,071 --> 00:29:15,273
The overall complexity of the environment and just the size of the space

609
00:29:15,313 --> 00:29:17,694
led to the player getting easily lost and frustrated.

610
00:29:19,162 --> 00:29:26,087
Above, or to the side, are two examples of Brines and I's interpretations.

611
00:29:26,707 --> 00:29:31,390
On first glance, they seem really similar. After all, we were following the same concept art,

612
00:29:31,430 --> 00:29:36,134
we were trying to address the same issues with player pathing, readability, and mood.

613
00:29:36,614 --> 00:29:40,537
But this was one of the first times in productions where we had differing opinions on how to achieve it.

614
00:29:43,079 --> 00:29:48,382
Like we said, we talked a lot on this project, from favorite types of pizza to level direction.

615
00:29:49,375 --> 00:29:50,817
We were constantly in communication.

616
00:29:51,437 --> 00:29:53,099
We talked back and forth with each other

617
00:29:53,139 --> 00:29:55,181
about how we should tackle this issue and more.

618
00:29:55,581 --> 00:29:57,643
And there's countless Slack messages between us

619
00:29:57,683 --> 00:29:59,765
discussing every problem and every solution.

620
00:30:00,986 --> 00:30:02,748
We can't really stress how important this was,

621
00:30:02,868 --> 00:30:05,050
both because we made a majority of this game from home

622
00:30:05,811 --> 00:30:08,193
and because it made our work stronger when we worked together.

623
00:30:12,140 --> 00:30:13,981
So this was my first time leading a team,

624
00:30:14,121 --> 00:30:16,022
and I knew going in that I wanted to extend

625
00:30:16,062 --> 00:30:17,963
the same level of trust that I'd always had

626
00:30:18,103 --> 00:30:20,424
with our awesome art director, Grant Hollis.

627
00:30:21,224 --> 00:30:22,685
Approaching feedback to this team

628
00:30:22,745 --> 00:30:24,186
was always a little bit less of a,

629
00:30:24,366 --> 00:30:25,967
this is how I need you to fix this,

630
00:30:27,027 --> 00:30:30,029
and a little bit more of us identifying issues

631
00:30:30,209 --> 00:30:32,730
and starting a conversation about how best to resolve.

632
00:30:35,518 --> 00:30:39,660
In this example of Blizzard, it was very clear that we all understood what the problems were,

633
00:30:39,800 --> 00:30:45,403
and we're trying to solve it with lighting, and we know what the issues are.

634
00:30:46,164 --> 00:30:50,246
This is a perfect example and a great opportunity to let someone on the team follow through

635
00:30:50,306 --> 00:30:51,687
on the vision that they wanted to do.

636
00:30:53,905 --> 00:30:56,867
And it made all the difference, not just because this space turned out tremendous,

637
00:30:56,967 --> 00:31:00,908
utilizing our fog to create a strong sense of foreground, middle ground, background,

638
00:31:01,568 --> 00:31:06,090
and adding visible fixtures to add lighting that contrasted against the organic environment,

639
00:31:06,150 --> 00:31:09,532
but also because trust had been established and it carried through the rest of the project.

640
00:31:10,292 --> 00:31:13,973
We both talked later on after the game had launched about how cool this moment was on the project

641
00:31:13,993 --> 00:31:15,534
and how much it helped us grow as a team.

642
00:31:21,870 --> 00:31:23,051
Sorry about that.

643
00:31:23,091 --> 00:31:24,872
With FLEAZAR really starting to take shape

644
00:31:24,912 --> 00:31:27,093
at a broad strokes level, it was time to start digging

645
00:31:27,153 --> 00:31:29,274
into making each area within the level

646
00:31:29,314 --> 00:31:30,734
feel distinct and exciting.

647
00:31:31,295 --> 00:31:33,376
The different districts, the Honeycomb Mission,

648
00:31:33,436 --> 00:31:35,757
the Underground Lava Cave, the Grand Vista,

649
00:31:35,837 --> 00:31:39,018
they all work together to create a cohesive vision,

650
00:31:39,098 --> 00:31:41,219
but one with enough variety in the color palette

651
00:31:41,640 --> 00:31:43,380
and contrast that individual spaces

652
00:31:43,420 --> 00:31:44,521
were able to stand on their own.

653
00:31:46,839 --> 00:31:49,400
And that leads us to one of the more exciting and challenging

654
00:31:49,460 --> 00:31:51,701
opportunities on this project, figuring out

655
00:31:51,721 --> 00:31:53,961
how to compare and contrast not just the levels

656
00:31:54,001 --> 00:31:57,923
with each other, but with levels that have multiple dimensions.

657
00:31:58,903 --> 00:32:00,484
Ratchet & Clank is all about two things,

658
00:32:00,744 --> 00:32:03,685
blowing stuff up with crazy weapons and insane levels

659
00:32:03,725 --> 00:32:05,385
that encourage the player to explore.

660
00:32:06,246 --> 00:32:07,786
Each new world you go to is a chance

661
00:32:07,806 --> 00:32:09,167
to see something spectacular.

662
00:32:09,187 --> 00:32:11,827
And that meant after establishing one planet,

663
00:32:12,088 --> 00:32:14,088
we needed to make sure that it felt entirely different

664
00:32:14,108 --> 00:32:14,648
from the rest.

665
00:32:15,485 --> 00:32:18,107
Each level had to have its own unique color scheme and identity.

666
00:32:18,428 --> 00:32:23,031
In cases like Blizzard, we even had to compare some levels against their own interdimensional counterpart.

667
00:32:24,032 --> 00:32:29,096
Doing these constant checks helped us make sure that each space felt like an entirely new alien world,

668
00:32:29,576 --> 00:32:32,579
as well as making sure that our lighting felt consistent throughout the game.

669
00:32:34,920 --> 00:32:39,944
Something really special about Rift Apart was how much time we had to accomplish real polish on this project.

670
00:32:40,818 --> 00:32:43,319
As many of you know, that doesn't always happen in production.

671
00:32:43,820 --> 00:32:45,781
Whether that's a AAA game or a midterm,

672
00:32:45,961 --> 00:32:47,802
you're often running right up to the wire.

673
00:32:48,703 --> 00:32:50,464
But because of our faithfulness to the pipeline,

674
00:32:50,904 --> 00:32:52,225
our constant checking of the game,

675
00:32:52,625 --> 00:32:54,086
and the dedication of the team,

676
00:32:54,447 --> 00:32:55,727
we had a little bit of extra time

677
00:32:55,767 --> 00:32:57,008
to make things as good as we could.

678
00:32:57,989 --> 00:33:00,270
That meant we were able to go back to each balanced area

679
00:33:00,410 --> 00:33:03,072
and really dial in and explore what we wanted to do.

680
00:33:03,913 --> 00:33:06,394
It was through careful planning and many slack threads

681
00:33:06,714 --> 00:33:10,076
that we were able to take something from good to great.

682
00:33:11,400 --> 00:33:17,946
When you're deep in production, it's easy to get overwhelmed with design, player pathing, and technical work.

683
00:33:18,947 --> 00:33:22,430
It's so much to keep track of that it all makes art take a back seat in your brain.

684
00:33:23,251 --> 00:33:28,036
While the previous image was... it was fine. It wasn't where we wanted it artistically.

685
00:33:29,157 --> 00:33:34,803
With this added time, we were able to dial in on exactly what our key areas of focus were and put in the work to fix them.

686
00:33:36,036 --> 00:33:38,418
Sometimes that meant doing more post-process work,

687
00:33:39,018 --> 00:33:40,980
tweaking the color schemes of specific areas

688
00:33:41,020 --> 00:33:42,200
to make them feel more unique.

689
00:33:43,001 --> 00:33:44,482
Other times it was fog adjustments

690
00:33:44,522 --> 00:33:46,363
to really dial in the mood of an area.

691
00:33:47,204 --> 00:33:48,225
In this specific spot,

692
00:33:48,665 --> 00:33:50,726
we needed to make a more cohesive color scheme,

693
00:33:50,766 --> 00:33:52,828
which involved changing the emissive signs

694
00:33:53,228 --> 00:33:54,209
and the light they gave off

695
00:33:54,269 --> 00:33:56,170
for a more focused, polished look.

696
00:33:59,294 --> 00:34:02,216
Later in production, many of our biggest cinematics started coming in,

697
00:34:02,416 --> 00:34:06,859
and it became a huge undertaking that needed a lot of quick turnaround and fantastic results.

698
00:34:07,539 --> 00:34:10,081
It was at this point I decided I was going to have Oz and Miki,

699
00:34:10,221 --> 00:34:12,463
two incredibly skilled cinematic lighters,

700
00:34:12,523 --> 00:34:16,325
begin focusing on taking these major parts of the project to final.

701
00:34:16,926 --> 00:34:20,588
They took on the significant role of not only lighting these cinematics,

702
00:34:20,668 --> 00:34:24,971
but like we kind of mentioned before, functioning almost as quality control for the final image.

703
00:34:25,737 --> 00:34:28,880
This meant tackling a lot of things that aren't really associated with lighting,

704
00:34:28,980 --> 00:34:32,862
like making material adjustments, making fur that looked wet when it was raining,

705
00:34:33,583 --> 00:34:37,566
animating the fur to blow around if the characters were up high or in a storm,

706
00:34:38,106 --> 00:34:43,650
and always, always, always making sure that our two Lombaxes had great eye spec.

707
00:34:46,311 --> 00:34:50,294
Meanwhile, Brian and myself turned our attention to wrapping up our level work.

708
00:34:50,915 --> 00:34:55,238
We would regularly play the game, creating extremely long pages of notes for us to address,

709
00:34:55,658 --> 00:34:57,940
as well as items of feedback for other teams.

710
00:34:58,601 --> 00:35:02,764
Then we'd split that work up, knock everything out we could, and do it all over again.

711
00:35:03,825 --> 00:35:07,548
We did this repeatedly for the final month or so of production, and I think I can speak

712
00:35:07,588 --> 00:35:11,331
for Brian when I say that not only was this some of the most fulfilling polish work I've

713
00:35:11,371 --> 00:35:13,533
ever done on a project, but it was some of the most fun.

714
00:35:16,689 --> 00:35:22,112
Nowhere is there a better example of collaboration really bringing a space to the finish line than Nefarious City.

715
00:35:22,612 --> 00:35:26,694
One of the first levels that the player sees in the game, and a level we just needed to knock out of the park.

716
00:35:27,574 --> 00:35:32,636
This was one of the biggest challenges in the game because it had to feel moody and atmospheric, but also full of life.

717
00:35:33,256 --> 00:35:38,699
That's a lot of hats to wear for a level, not to mention that the player needed to be able to navigate through all of this visual noise.

718
00:35:39,579 --> 00:35:44,502
One of the unique things about this project was the amount of collaboration that was done.

719
00:35:44,887 --> 00:35:49,071
We spent months passing this level back and forth between us, building on each other's strengths,

720
00:35:49,571 --> 00:35:52,874
getting ideas from one another, and lending a hand too many times to count.

721
00:35:53,555 --> 00:35:58,159
Closing in on the end of production, I handed this level off fully to Anna to bring home,

722
00:35:58,199 --> 00:35:59,760
and she absolutely nailed this space.

723
00:36:00,241 --> 00:36:04,124
It went from looking like a great level to just an absolutely incredible environment.

724
00:36:06,974 --> 00:36:10,137
Nefarious City is one of the things I'm most proudest of in the game,

725
00:36:10,638 --> 00:36:12,280
not just because it's a great level,

726
00:36:12,380 --> 00:36:15,884
but because of the challenge and collaboration it took to get there.

727
00:36:16,785 --> 00:36:18,347
I started this project as an intern,

728
00:36:18,727 --> 00:36:21,210
and after I finished college, I was given the opportunity

729
00:36:21,690 --> 00:36:23,412
to come back and finish what I had started.

730
00:36:24,429 --> 00:36:28,912
I learned more about lighting, teamwork, and the struggles of game development on this

731
00:36:28,952 --> 00:36:32,455
game in this very level than I ever had in a classroom.

732
00:36:33,096 --> 00:36:37,199
To me, Rift Apart isn't just a great game, but it's a sign of the personal and professional

733
00:36:37,239 --> 00:36:40,021
growth it took for me to get right here on the stage today.

734
00:36:40,762 --> 00:36:42,924
And it's something I couldn't be more happy to share with you.

